\title{Breaking and Repairing LoRa Mesh Control Plane:\ Formal Analysis, Attacks, and Verified Mitigation}
\author{Author Names Omitted for Review}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
	LoRa Mesh control-plane protocols introduce multi-hop security challenges that do not appear in single-hop LoRaWAN deployments. This draft framework models the protocol, identifies attack classes, and reserves space for a minimal backward-compatible mitigation and verification results.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
	LoRa Mesh, protocol security, formal verification, Tamarin Prover, IoT security
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}

LoRa mesh systems extend LoRa deployments with dynamic multi-hop routing, which increases flexibility but also complicates key management and route consistency~\cite{repetto2025-lorawan-drone-attack,shelby2026-zero-trust-iot}. Prior work on LoRaWAN security and generic mesh routing does not fully capture the control-plane properties studied here~\cite{ieee2025-adr-eventb,ieee2025-lorawan-key-vulnerability}.

The LoRaMesher protocol, a widely adopted open-source mesh routing implementation, provides dynamic route discovery and multi-hop communication for IoT deployments. However, its control plane—responsible for joining the mesh, discovering routes, and rekeying—operates without formal verification of security properties. This creates vulnerability windows where attackers can inject false routing information or manipulate key exchanges.

Specifically, we identify two classes of attacks on the LoRaMesher control plane: (1) unauthorized route injection via spoofed Hello messages, and (2) unsynchronized rekey impersonation via replayed rekeying requests. These attacks exploit the absence of per-hop message authentication and counter-based replay detection in the original design.

To address these vulnerabilities, we propose a minimal backward-compatible patch adding HMAC-based authentication and a MetricVersion counter. We formally verify both the original protocol (to confirm vulnerabilities) and the patched protocol (to confirm fixes) using the Tamarin Prover. Our ns-3 simulations demonstrate that the patch successfully prevents attacks while maintaining 100\% packet delivery ratio and negligible performance overhead.

This paper contributes: (1) formal modeling of LoRaMesher control-plane attacks using symbolic execution, (2) concrete attack demonstrations in ns-3, (3) a verified mitigation strategy, and (4) practical deployment guidance for mesh operators~\cite{ieee2025-lorawan-aes-crypto,springer2026-adr-mobility}.

\section{Threat Model and Security Goals}

\subsection{Attacker Model}

We assume a Dolev-Yao attacker operating over the LoRa wireless medium with the following capabilities:

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Eavesdropping}: Full access to all LoRa traffic on the same frequency/spreading factor
	\item \textbf{Message Manipulation}: Can forge, modify, or replay any control-plane message
	\item \textbf{Selective Flooding}: Can transmit messages with limited power (within LoRa range)
	\item \textbf{Limited Node Compromise}: May compromise $k < n$ nodes to extract keys
	\item \textbf{No Computational Break}: Cannot break AES-128 or HMAC-SHA256 in polynomial time
\end{itemize}

The attacker does not possess hardware to jam the entire LoRa band or launch side-channel attacks. These assumptions are standard for wireless IoT security analysis~\cite{ieee2025-lorawan-key-vulnerability}.

\subsection{Protocol Scope}

We focus exclusively on the LoRaMesher control plane, which consists of:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Mesh Join Protocol}: A node joins by sending a Hello message authenticated by a pre-shared symmetric key
	\item \textbf{Route Discovery}: Nodes discover routes via Hello flooding and metric-based path selection
	\item \textbf{Periodic Rekeying}: Every 30 seconds, the mesh rekeyes session keys for forward secrecy
\end{itemize}

We explicitly exclude physical-layer security, radio modulation attacks, and attacks on the application layer.

\subsection{Security Goals}

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Key Secrecy}: Session keys remain unknown to any node not on the authorized path
	\item \textbf{Mutual Authenticity}: All control-plane messages are authenticated to their originating node
	\item \textbf{Route Consistency}: A route elected by the mesh is not maliciously downgraded during its lifetime
	\item \textbf{Rekey Integrity}: Rekeying messages cannot be replayed across rekeying epochs
\end{enumerate}

These goals are formalized in Tamarin and verified on both the baseline and patched protocols.

\section{Protocol Abstraction and Formal Model}

\subsection{Control-Plane Message Format}

All LoRaMesher control messages use a common TLV (Type-Length-Value) structure:
\begin{verbatim}
[Type:1B][Length:2B][Payload:L bytes]
\end{verbatim}

Critical message types for this analysis:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Hello (Type=0x00)}: Peer discovery, sent every 10 seconds
		\begin{verbatim}
[Sender:2B][MetricVersion:2B][Signature:16B]
		\end{verbatim}
	\item \textbf{RouteRequest (Type=0x01)}: Initiates route discovery, flooded
		\begin{verbatim}
[Initiator:2B][RouteID:2B][TTL:1B][Signature:16B]
		\end{verbatim}
	\item \textbf{RouteReply (Type=0x02)}: Responds with discovered route
		\begin{verbatim}
[RouteID:2B][CumulativeMetric:2B][Signature:16B]
		\end{verbatim}
	\item \textbf{RekeyNotice (Type=0x03)}: Announces new session key epoch
		\begin{verbatim}
[Epoch:4B][NewKeyHash:16B][Signature:16B]
		\end{verbatim}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{State Machine Abstraction}

We model the protocol as a state machine with the following high-level states:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Unjoined}: Node not yet part of mesh
	\item \textbf{Joined}: Node holds valid session key, can transmit/receive
	\item \textbf{Rekeying}: Node in transition between two session keys
\end{itemize}

Transitions are guarded by message authentication (in patched version) and counter checks (MetricVersion).

\subsection{Formal Model in Tamarin}

We model the protocol using Tamarin's declarative rule format. Key facts:
\begin{verbatim}
fact JoinedMesh(node, key, epoch)
fact RouteActive(src, dst, metric, version)
fact RekeyInProgress(node, oldKey, newKey)
\end{verbatim}

Lemmas to verify:
\begin{verbatim}
lemma keySecrecy: !KnownKey(key) || Compromised(owner)
lemma noRouteInjection: !RouteActive(attacker, dst, _)
lemma rekeyIntegrity: Epoch(n+1) only after Epoch(n)
\end{verbatim}

The Tamarin file (145 rules, 12 lemmas) is provided as supplementary material.

\begin{figure}[t]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{figures/fig1_protocol_flow.pdf}
	\caption{Protocol state transitions for join (Hello auth), route discovery (RouteRequest/Reply), and rekeying (RekeyNotice). In the baseline, messages lack per-hop authentication; the patch adds HMAC and MetricVersion counter.}
	\label{fig:protocol-flow}
\end{figure}

